thodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Griffith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffieth","meanings":["Variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griff","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone living near a pit or hollow, from Middle English <i>grif</i> ‘pit, hollow, narrow valley’ (Old Norse <i>gryfja</i>), or a habitational name from Griff in Warwickshire, Griffe in Derbyshire, or Griff Farm in Rievaulx, North Yorkshire, all probably named with this word.","Welsh and English: from the Welsh personal name <i>Gryff</i>, a short form of <i>Gruffudd</i>. See   Griffith  .","German: variant of   Greif   1."]},{"name":"Kerfoot","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire):","habitational name, probably from Carefoot, near Myerscough (Lancashire).","possibly a variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffes","meanings":["Welsh: altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffeth","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffiths","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan and western England): Anglicized form of the patronymic <i>(ap) Gruffudd</i>, from Old Welsh <i>Grippiud</i> (see   Griffith  )."]},{"name":"Griffth","meanings":["Variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffitt","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas ap Griffith was born about 1400, in Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Thomas ap Griffith."},"et":{"about 1400–":"umbes 1400–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1426":"1426","1404":"1404","abt 1426":"umbes 1426","1400":"1400","about 1400":"umbes 1400","Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales":"Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1400–":"noin 1400–Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1426":"1426","1404":"1404","abt 1426":"noin 1426","1400":"1400","about 1400":"noin 1400","Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales":"Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1400–":"environ 1400–Décédé","1404–Female":"1404–Décédée","1426–Female":"1426–Décédée","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1426":"1426","1404":"1404","abt 1426":"environ 1426","1400":"1400","about 1400":"environ 1400","Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales":"Glyn, Denbighshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Thomas ap Griffith est né environ 1400, à Glyn, Denbighshire, Galles. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mrs. Thomas ap Griffith."},"de":{"about 1400–":"um 1400–Verstorben","1404–Female":"1404–Verstorben","1426–Female":"1426–Verstorben","1400–Male":"1400–Verstorben","1426":"1426","1404":"1404","abt 1426":"um 1426","1400":"1400","about 1400":"um 1400","Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales":"Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Thomas ap Griffith wurde um 1400 in Glyn, Denbighshire, Wales geboren. Er hatte mit Mrs. Thomas ap Griffith mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1400–":"about 1400–Desede","1404–Female":"1404–Desede","1426–Female":"1426–Desede","1400–Male":"1400–Desede","1426":"1426","1404":"1404","abt 1426":"about 1426"